    <div class="sec-t">About</div>
    <p>Tromsø is located at 69.6°N, approximately 350 kilometres above the Arctic Circle. At this latitude, <strong>the sun does not set for approximately 63 days each year</strong>, from around 20 May to 22 July. During this period the sun traces a continuous arc around the horizon, dipping to its lowest point — typically 3 to 7 degrees above the horizon — around midnight local time. This produces a persistent orange-gold low-angle light across the landscape that differs from standard daytime light at all hours. Outside this core window, Tromsø experiences very long days from late April through late August, with only a brief period of civil twilight at night.</p>
    <p>The phenomenon is caused by the axial tilt of the Earth. Tromsø's position within the auroral oval means it also experiences the polar night — the opposite effect — from approximately 27 November to 15 January, when the sun does not rise. <strong>The midnight sun season coincides with Tromsø's peak summer tourism period</strong>. Fjellheisen cable car summit at 421 metres above sea level is the most frequently visited elevated viewpoint; from there the sun is visible on the horizon with unobstructed 360-degree views over the island and surrounding fjords. Telegrafbukta beach at the southern tip of Tromsøya provides an accessible free ground-level alternative with westward views across the water toward the Lyngen Alps.</p>
    <p>No ticket, booking, or guide is required to see the midnight sun. It is visible from any outdoor location in Tromsø with a clear sky. Cloud cover is the primary limiting factor; <strong>Tromsø averages approximately 50–60% cloud cover in summer</strong>, so clear nights are not guaranteed. A sleep mask or blackout curtains are advisable for visitors sensitive to continuous light. Most Tromsø hotels provide blackout curtains. The official tourism organisation for the region, Visit Tromsø, publishes practical visitor information at visittromso.no.</p>
